In article <1te7m9INN9bb@golden.kaleida.com>, Jay Fenton <Fenton@Kaleida writes:
>Why not use a public key system, leaving the private key at home in the
>safe.

Fine for some applications, but consider this scenario: Chris
keeps his digital cash in his electronic wallet, encrypted.
Diane forces him at gunpoint to hand over his wallet and reveal
the key.  But when Diane logs into the wallet and checks the
digital cash balance, she finds it's only $20.48.
